The third argument to `mergeMap` is the concurrency limit — at most 3 uploads run in parallel; additional files queue until a slot frees up.

`Subject<T>` has no initial value and doesn't replay — a subscriber only gets values emitted *after* it subscribes. `BehaviorSubject<T>` holds a current value (required at construction) and immediately emits that value to every new subscriber.

For a `currentUser` stream where any new consumer should instantly see the active user, use `BehaviorSubject`.

```ts
import { BehaviorSubject, Subject } from 'rxjs';

interface User { id: string; name: string }

// WRONG: late subscribers miss the login
const badStream = new Subject<User | null>();
badStream.next({ id: '1', name: 'Ada' });
badStream.subscribe((u) => console.log('late (Subject):', u));
// ^ logs nothing

// RIGHT: BehaviorSubject replays current value
export const currentUser$ = new BehaviorSubject<User | null>(null);
currentUser$.next({ id: '1', name: 'Ada' });
currentUser$.subscribe((u) => console.log('late (Behavior):', u));
// ^ logs: { id: '1', name: 'Ada' }

// read synchronously:
console.log(currentUser$.getValue());
```

Bonus: `ReplaySubject(n)` if you need the last N values, not just the latest one.

